The results are reported intable 2. In nonseasonal (business cycle) frequencies, the contemporaneous growth of market demand has a positive and statistically significant impact on new product introductions in three industries (Food, Electrical Machinery, and Instruments). The growth rate of market demand lagged once also has a positive and statistically significant impact on new products in three industries (Food, Chemicals, and Transportation Equipment). Finally, the growth rate of market demand lagged twice has a positive and statistically significant impact on new product introductions in only one industry (Food). Apparently, market demand plays an important role in companies’ decisions to introduce their new products. It seems that companies respond with a slight time lag (1–2 months) to market expansions before they introduce their new products. However, these results seem to die out with the passage of time. Table 2
