Finally, market and aggregate demand explain a significant part of the nonseasonal variability of new product introductions at least in some industries. The
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\overline{R}^{\, 2}$ \end{document}
               in the appropriate regressions shows that demand fluctuations explain approximately 11% (for Transportation Equipment) to 43% (for Electrical Machinery) of the nonseasonal variability of new product introductions. New product introductions in Electrical Machinery are the most responsive to demand fluctuations, with new products in Transportation Equipment being the least responsive.

