                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\overline{R}^{\, 2}$ \end{document}
               in the regressions, demand fluctuations explain twice as much of the seasonal activity in new product introductions versus the cyclical one. This is consistent with hypothesis 3, indicating that companies manage to synchronize their new product introductions much better with seasonal demand expansions. Seasonal cycles are more regular than business cycles, and therefore their timing is much more predictable. Consequently, companies synchronize the timing of launching their new products much more easily with the seasonal demand peaks.

